abstract:
A new bottom-up visual saliency model, Graph-Based Visual Saliency (GBVS), is proposed. It consists of two steps: first forming activation maps on certain feature&#13;
channels, and then normalizing them in a way which highlights conspicuity and admits combination with other maps. The model is simple, and biologically plausible&#13;
insofar as it is naturally parallelized. This model powerfully predicts human fixations on 749 variations of 108 natural images, achieving 98% of the ROC area&#13;
of a human-based control, whereas the classical algorithms of Itti &amp; Koch ([2], [3], [4]) achieve only 84%.
